{"ts":"2026-06-27T20:36:50.125Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"tool","toolName":"read_files","toolCallId":"rz89r6rv","output":[{"query":"/Users/ayushbansal/Documents/GitHub/hirezapp_landing_page/docs/PHASE_5_MVP_BACKEND.md:1-100","result":"  1 | # GFF AI Platform: Phase 5 Local MVP Backend Setup & Developer Guide\n  2 | \n  3 | This document establishes the strategic, technical, and operational manual for configuring and running the **Phase 5 Local MVP Backend** of the GFF AI Platform. \n  4 | \n  5 | To support the premium, high-fidelity presentation layer developed in Phase 4, Phase 5 introduces a lightweight, high-performance local FastAPI backend. This local server connects to a local SQLite database, processes authentications via JSON Web Tokens (JWT), and hosts multi-tenant workspaces so that developers and stakeholders can test complete client and administrative flows locally.\n  6 | \n  7 | ---\n  8 | \n  9 | ## 1. Executive Narrative & Architectural Scope\n 10 | \n 11 | ### 1.1. Decoupled Sandbox Metaphor\n 12 | In alignment with the GFF AI **Sovereign Operating System** philosophy, the Phase 5 backend is engineered as a local developer sandbox. It replicates multi-tenant access control and core database persistence without introducing complex, expensive production dependencies. \n 13 | \n 14 | This local engine acts as the \"State Synchronizer\" for the frontend cockpit, enabling real-time REST API handshakes, dynamic database logging, and role-based clearance verification.\n 15 | \n 16 | ### 1.2. Scope & Boundaries (MVP Development Phase)\n 17 | The Phase 5 backend is designed **exclusively for local development, demonstration, and offline evaluation**. It provides a solid architectural foundation while intentionally omitting several enterprise cloud-scale features.\n 18 | \n 19 | > ⚠️ **Phase Scope Limitations**:\n 20 | > *   **Local-Only Database**: Uses a local SQLite file (`dev.db`). No RDS/Postgres database setups are used.\n 21 | > *   **No AWS Integrations**: Does not utilize real AWS resources (such as DynamoDB, S3 file buckets, or AWS IAM roles).\n 22 | > *   **No Storage Backend**: File uploads and secure legal document storage are handled via frontend-only simulation placeholders; no physical file-saving backend is active.\n 23 | > *   **No External Payment Gateways**: Computational \"Epoch\" invoicing and billing tables exist in SQLite, but there is no integration with billing aggregators like Stripe or Chargebee.\n 24 | > *   **No Real Emails/OTP/SSO**: There is no live SMTP mailer, Multi-Factor/One-Time Password (OTP) verification, or OAuth2/SSO identity providers. Auth relies strictly on standard OAuth2 JWT tokens with local bcrypt hashing.\n 25 | > *   **No Live Backend for GFF AI Tools**: Tool execution engines, prompt generators, and agent configurations run within mock sandboxes inside the frontend client.\n 26 | > *   **No Production Auth Hardening**: Features like Rate-limiting, IP-restrictions, secure HttpOnly cookie session management, or Hardware Security Module (HSM) signing are deferred to production deployment phases.\n 27 | \n 28 | ---\n 29 | \n 30 | ## 2. Prerequisites\n 31 | \n 32 | Ensure you have the following environments installed locally on your system:\n 33 | *   **Node.js**: `v18.x` or later (for running the Next.js frontend)\n 34 | *   **Python**: `v3.12.x` or later (for running the FastAPI backend)\n 35 | *   **pip**: Python package manager\n 36 | *   **SQLite3**: Installed on your system (typically comes bundled with Python)\n 37 | \n 38 | ---\n 39 | \n 40 | ## 3. Local Environment Variables Configuration\n 41 | \n 42 | To bridge the Next.js frontend and the FastAPI backend, you must establish environment templates in both repositories.\n 43 | \n 44 | ### 3.1. Create Backend Environment\n 45 | Copy the backend configuration template inside the `backend` folder:\n 46 | ```bash\n 47 | cp backend/.env.example backend/.env\n 48 | ```\n 49 | \n 50 | Your `backend/.env` file will look like this:\n 51 | ```env\n 52 | # GFF AI Local MVP Backend Configuration\n 53 | PROJECT_NAME=\"GFF AI Enterprise API\"\n 54 | API_V1_STR=\"/api/v1\"\n 55 | ENVIRONMENT=\"development\"\n 56 | DATABASE_URL=\"sqlite:///dev.db\"\n 57 | \n 58 | # Local JWT configuration\n 59 | JWT_SECRET=\"gff_ai_super_secret_local_key_for_jwt_tokens_2026\"\n 60 | ACCESS_TOKEN_EXPIRE_MINUTES=11520  # 8 Days\n 61 | \n 62 | # Allowed CORS Origins\n 63 | CORS_ORIGINS=\"http://localhost:3000,http://127.0.0.1:3000\"\n 64 | FRONTEND_BASE_URL=\"http://localhost:3000\"\n 65 | ```\n 66 | \n 67 | ### 3.2. Create Frontend Environment\n 68 | Copy the frontend environment template in the project root:\n 69 | ```bash\n 70 | cp .env.example .env\n 71 | ```\n 72 | \n 73 | To enable active backend connectivity in the Next.js frontend, configure `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL` in the root `.env` to point to the local FastAPI port:\n 74 | ```env\n 75 | # API Integration\n 76 | NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL=http://localhost:8000/api/v1\n 77 | NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_ENV=development\n 78 | NEXT_PUBLIC_PORTAL_UPLOADS_ENABLED=true\n 79 | ```\n 80 | \n 81 | *Note: If `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL` is omitted or commented out, the frontend gracefully falls back to its client-side mock handlers.*\n 82 | \n 83 | ---\n 84 | \n 85 | ## 4. Local Backend Setup & Installation\n 86 | \n 87 | To streamline development, root-level convenience scripts are provided in the master `package.json` file. These scripts manage virtual environments and package installations automatically.\n 88 | \n 89 | ### 4.1. Automatic Automated Installation (Recommended)\n 90 | From the **root directory** of the project, run:\n 91 | ```bash\n 92 | npm run backend:install\n 93 | ```\n 94 | This automated command:\n 95 | 1.  Enters the `backend/` directory.\n 96 | 2.  Creates a Python virtual environment (`venv/`) if it does not exist.\n 97 | 3.  Upgrades pip and installs all required dependencies from `backend/requirements.txt`.\n 98 | 4.  Generates a `.env` file from `.env.example` if it is missing.\n 99 | \n100 | ### 4.2. Manual Installation","success":true}],"durationMs":6}}
