bles and ASCII diagrams to illustrate the single-table design pattern for PORTAL_ITEMS, and decoupled lookup tables for USERS and CLIENTS. I plan to match the structure of the Phase 5 docs with sections like the Executive Narrative, System Architecture, DynamoDB Tables, S3 Storage Bucket, and Environment Configurations.\n\n\n**Detailing Table Structures**\n\nI'm now detailing the structure of the DynamoDB tables and confirming the required information for documentation. I'll outline `GFF_USERS` with its primary key 'email', `GFF_CLIENTS` with 'client_id', and `GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS` with 'PK', 'SK', and GSI1. I'm focusing on ensuring these tables are easy to read on mobile devices, by keeping the schema tables compact, and focusing on concise documentation. I have the files I need to modify, and I'm aware of what not to touch, so I can keep my focus on writing the document. I am documenting the storage of Projects, AI Operations, Documents metadata, Invoices metadata, Support Tickets, and Governance Items in `GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`, and one S3 bucket for portal documents, with essential backend and frontend environment keys.\n\n\n**Defining Table Contents**\n\nI'm now detailing the contents of the DynamoDB tables for inclusion in the document. I will be documenting `GFF_USERS`, detailing attributes such as `email`, `full_name`, `role`, `client_id`, `created_at`, and `status`. For `GFF_CLIENTS`, I'll include `client_id`, `company_name`, `industry`, `tier`, `status`, and `created_at`. I'm working to make sure these are easy to read. I'll summarize their purposes, focusing on concise documentation.\n\n\n**Describing Item Attributes**\n\nNow I'm detailing the specific attributes within `GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`. For AI Operations, I'm noting PK, SK, GSI1PK, and GSI1SK, along with attributes like `name`, `status`, `agent_count`, `runtime`, `cpu_usage`, and `memory_usage`. I'm documenting the schema for documents, invoices, and support tickets, keeping each description concise and precise