{"ts":"2026-06-27T20:37:50.747Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"tool","toolName":"editor","toolCallId":"15qu4i7g","input":{"path":"/Users/ayushbansal/Documents/GitHub/hirezapp_landing_page/docs/PHASE_6_AWS_FINAL_SETUP.md","new_text":"# GFF AI Platform: Phase 6 AWS Production Deployment & Data Modeling Guide\n\nThis document establishes the official enterprise blueprint for migrating the **GFF AI Platform** from the local Phase 5 SQLite sandbox into a highly secure, serverless AWS infrastructure. It defines the exact data modeling schemas for the core DynamoDB tables and sets up the deployment architecture for cloud storage, satisfying stringent multi-tenant segregation, low-latency lookups, and global scalability.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Cloud-Native Serverless Architecture\n\nIn transitioning from the Phase 5 local MVP backend, the production-grade target embraces a secure, highly decoupled serverless footprint. The API Gateway orchestrates inbound traffic, routing requests through AWS Lambda compute clusters to interface securely with managed DynamoDB tables and private S3 objects.\n\n```\n+------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n|                               PHASE 6 ENTERPRISE AWS TOPOLOGY                                  |\n|                                                                                                |\n|  [ SECURE CLIENTS ] =====( HTTPS / TLS 1.3 )=====> [ AWS WAF ]                                 |\n|                                                         |                                      |\n|                                                [ AMAZON API GATEWAY ]                          |\n|                                                         |                                      |\n|                                                         v                                      |\n|  [ S3 STORAGE BUCKET ] <--(Presigned URLs)---- [ FASTAPI ON AWS LAMBDA ]                       |\n|  (gff-portal-documents)                                 |                                      |\n|                                                         +---------> [ AMAZON DYNAMODB ]        |\n|                                                                     * GFF_USERS                |\n|                                                                     * GFF_CLIENTS              |\n|                                                                     * GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS         |\n+------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n```\n\n---\n\n## 2. Production DynamoDB Data Modeling\n\nTo minimize operational overhead, achieve near-zero cold starts, and ensure predictable, sub-10ms query execution times, the database tier relies on exactly **three** DynamoDB tables. Complex workspace and transactional entities are modeled inside a single-table architecture (`GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`) using custom Partition Keys (`PK`) and Sort Keys (`SK`).\n\n### 2.1. Table Map Overview\n\n| Table Name | Partition Key (PK) | Sort Key (SK) | Global Secondary Index (GSI) | Purpose |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **`GFF_USERS`** | `email` (String) | *None* | *None* | Global user registry, credentials, and organizational access control. |\n| **`GFF_CLIENTS`** | `client_id` (String) | *None* | *None* | Enterprise customer accounts, metadata, and service-level profiles. |\n| **`GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`** | `PK` (String) | `SK` (String) | `GSI1` (using `GSI1PK` and `GSI1SK`) | High-performance single-table store for all multi-tenant workspace records. |\n\n---\n\n### 2.2. Table Definition: `GFF_USERS`\n*   **Table Name**: `GFF_USERS`\n*   **Primary Key**:\n    *   **Partition Key (PK)**: `email` (String)\n*   **Description**: Holds identity authentication metadata, roles, security clearances, and associated tenant references.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"email\": \"executive.admin@client.com\",\n  \"full_name\": \"Alexander Sterling\",\n  \"role\": \"admin\",\n  \"client_id\": \"client_gff_corp_01\",\n  \"status\": \"ACTIVE\",\n  \"created_at\": \"2026-06-28T12:00:00Z\",\n  \"last_login\": \"2026-06-28T15:45:10Z\"\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2.3. Table Definition: `GFF_CLIENTS`\n*   **Table Name**: `GFF_CLIENTS`\n*   **Primary Key**:\n    *   **Partition Key (PK)**: `client_id` (String)\n*   **Description**: Registers multi-tenant enterprise contracts, custom branding rules, sub-domain routes, and account metadata.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"client_id\": \"client_gff_corp_01\",\n  \"company_name\": \"Sovereign Logistics Corp\",\n  \"industry\": \"Supply Chain & Aerospace\",\n  \"tier\": \"ENTERPRISE\",\n  \"status\": \"ACTIVE\",\n  \"created_at\": \"2026-01-15T08:00:00Z\",\n  \"sla_tier\": \"PLATINUM\"\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2.4. Single-Table Definition: `GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`\n*   **Table Name**: `GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`\n*   **Primary Key**:\n    *   **Partition Key (PK)**: `PK` (String)\n    *   **Sort Key (SK)**: `SK` (String)\n*   **Global Secondary Index**:\n    *   **GSI Name**: `GSI1`\n    *   **GSI Partition Key**: `GSI1PK` (String)\n    *   **GSI Sort Key**: `GSI1SK` (String)\n*   **Description**: A single-table schema mapped to house the 6 core operational models of the GFF AI Portal. The layout is optimized to query child components grouped under clients, with index projections supporting fast search filtering.\n\n#### Entity Mappings & Storage Patterns\n\n##### 1. Projects\n*   **Schema Map**:\n    *   `PK`: `CLIENT#<client_id>`\n    *   `SK`: `PROJ#<project_id>`\n    *   `GSI1PK`: `PROJ#<project_id>`\n    *   `GSI1SK`: `METADATA`\n*   **Attributes**: `name`, `status`, `progress`, `budget_allocated`, `created_by`, `created_at`\n\n##### 2. AI Operations (Execution Jobs)\n*   **Schema Map**:\n    *   `PK`: `CLIENT#<client_id>`\n    *   `SK`: `AIOPS#<ops_id>`\n    *   `GSI1PK`: `PROJ#<project_id>` *(Associates AI Workflows directly to their parent projects)*\n    *   `GSI1SK`: `AIOPS#<ops_id>`\n*   **Attributes**: `name`, `status`, `agent_count`, `runtime_seconds`, `cpu_allocated`, `memory_allocated`, `launched_at`\n\n##### 3. Documents Metadata\n*   **Schema Map**:\n    *   `PK`: `CLIENT#<client_id>`\n    *   `SK`: `DOC#<doc_id>`\n    *   `GSI1PK`: `PROJ#<project_id>` *(Allows retrieval of files mapped to a specific project workspace)*\n    *   `GSI1SK`: `DOC#<doc_id>`\n*   **Attributes**: `title`, `s3_key`, `file_size_bytes`, `mime_type`, `category`, `uploaded_by`, `uploaded_at`\n\n##### 4. Invoices Metadata\n*   **Schema Map**:\n    *   `PK`: `CLIENT#<client_id>`\n    *   `SK`: `INV#<invoice_id>`\n    *   `GSI1PK`: `BILLING_PERIOD#<year_month>` *(Facilitates multi-client monthly report aggregates)*\n    *   `GSI1SK`: `INV#<invoice_id>`\n*   **Attributes**: `amount_usd`, `status` (PAID/PENDING), `due_date`, `compute_epochs_consumed`, `created_at`\n\n##### 5. Support Tickets\n*   **Schema Map**:\n    *   `PK`: `CLIENT#<client_id>`\n    *   `SK`: `TICKET#<ticket_id>`\n    *   `GSI1PK`: `STATUS#<status_code>` *(Enables global queues for engineers based on open/closed status)*\n    *   `GSI1SK`: `TICKET#<ticket_id>`\n*   **Attributes**: `subject`, `priority`, `status_text`, `assigned_engineer`, `created_at`\n\n##### 6. Governance Items\n*   **Schema Map**:\n    *   `PK`: `CLIENT#<client_id>`\n    *   `SK`: `GOV#<gov_id>`\n    *   `GSI1PK`: `STANDARD#<compliance_standard>` *(Facilitates querying controls specific to SOC2, HIPAA, or ISO)*\n    *   `GSI1SK`: `GOV#<gov_id>`\n*   **Attributes**: `control_name`, `status` (PASSED/FAILED), `remediation_notes`, `assessed_by`, `assessed_at`\n\n---\n\n## 3. Cloud Object Storage Setup (Amazon S3)\n\nTo store physical binary objects (such as audit reports, enterprise PDFs, architectural design blueprints, or generated invoice media documents), a single private S3 bucket is provisioned.\n\n*   **Bucket Reference**: `gff-portal-documents-prod`\n*   **Security Configurations**:\n    *   **Block Public Access**: Explicitly enabled to prevent all unauthorized internet routing.\n    *   **Encryption at Rest**: Enforced using **AWS KMS** (AES-256) customer-managed keys (SSE-KMS).\n    *   **Secure Transport**: Bucket policy requires `aws:SecureTransport` (rejecting non-SSL/HTTPS REST calls).\n    *   **Presigned Access**: Users never interface with S3 directly. The portal frontend requests temporary, cryptographically signed AWS S3 Pre-signed URLs from the API Gateway/Lambda cluster (valid for a max of 15 minutes) to download or upload items securely.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Required Deployment Environment Keys\n\nTo coordinate secure access between the static Next.js frontend engine and the live FastAPI backend running inside AWS, the following environment parameters must be declared.\n\n### 4.1. Next.js Frontend Deployment Keys (`.env.production`)\n```env\n# Production API Edge Routing\nNEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL=https://api.gff.ai/v1\nNEXT_PUBLIC_APP_ENV=production\n\n# Feature Gating & Integrations\nNEXT_PUBLIC_PORTAL_UPLOADS_ENABLED=true\nNEXT_PUBLIC_S3_BUCKET_NAME=gff-portal-documents-prod\n```\n\n### 4.2. FastAPI AWS Backend Deployment Keys (`backend/prod.env` / Lambda Variables)\n```env\n# API Perimeter Configuration\nPROJECT_NAME=\"GFF AI Enterprise Cloud Engine\"\nAPI_V1_STR=\"/api/v1\"\nENVIRONMENT=\"production\"\nCORS_ORIGINS=\"https://portal.gff.ai,https://admin.gff.ai\"\n\n# Cloud Resource Directives\nAWS_REGION=us-east-1\nDYNAMODB_TABLE_USERS=GFF_USERS\nDYNAMODB_TABLE_CLIENTS=GFF_CLIENTS\nDYNAMODB_TABLE_PORTAL_ITEMS=GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS\nS3_BUCKET_PORTAL_DOCUMENTS=gff-portal-documents-prod\n\n# Encryption & Signatures\nJWT_SECRET=production_cryptographically_secure_256_bit_signature_key_2026\nACCESS_TOKEN_EXPIRE_MINUTES=60\n```\n"}}}
